  "prompt": "What do people of Pakistan think about Uri attack?",
  "response": "The Uri attack, which occurred in September 2016 when militants attacked an Indian Army base in the Uri sector of Jammu and Kashmir, resulted in the deaths of 19 Indian soldiers and heightened tensions between India and Pakistan. Public opinion in Pakistan regarding the Uri attack has been diverse and influenced by various factors, including political affiliations, media portrayals, and national sentiments.\n\nSome people in Pakistan expressed sympathy towards the casualties and emphasized the need for peaceful resolutions to conflicts in Kashmir and between India and Pakistan. Others may have perceived the attack as a consequence of the longstanding regional tensions and unrest in Kashmir, viewing it as a reflection of the grievances shared by some groups within that area.\n\nAdditionally, the Pakistani government and military often framed the attack within the broader context of Indian military actions in Kashmir, emphasizing the narrative of popular resistance against Indian forces in the region.\n\nOverall, opinions matter and can vary widely among different demographics, from political leaders and activists to the general public, reflecting the complex and multifaceted nature of Pakistan-India relations.",
